<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TEC Adopts Proposal To Elect New President 6 May </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2303092694 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 0500 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2303092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Transitional Executive Council [TEC] has adopted 
a resolution proposing that the National Assembly meet for the 
first time on 6 May in Cape Town, to elect South Africa's new 
president. The TEC said the constitution stipulated that the 
chief justice is required to convene the first meeting of the 
National Assembly within 10 days of the election. The president 
would be elected at that meeting. The TEC proposal suggested 
the formal inauguration and swearing in of the president be held 
on 10 May at the Union Buildings in Pretoria. The TEC said the 
first meeting of each provincial legislature would be held on, 
or before 5 May this year. 

</TEXT>

