<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Ends Meeting With Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2403162394 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 1215 GMT 24 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2403162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Gabon, the new cabinet has still not been formed 
11 days after Prime Minister Casimir Oye-Mba's reappointment by 
President Omar Bongo. Although certain reports had indicated 
that the new cabinet list would be released today, a communique 
has disclosed that the prime minister has adjourned the meeting 
he convened for this morning to confer with party leaders. The 
communique stressed that the meeting was adjourned due to the 
absence of opposition political leaders. Sources close to the 
prime minister, whom the head of state has asked to confer with 
all the political parties to establish a priority action 
program, indicate that the prime minister is continuing his 
consultations. Gabon is one of the African countries that will 
appear before the IMF next week to have their letters of intent 
examined. 

</TEXT>

