<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Spokesman: Cameroon Moving Troops Near Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2503121994 Paris AFP in French 1113 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2503121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 25 Mar (AFP)--The Nigerian Defense 
Headquarters asserted today that the Army has, for the past two 
days, noticed an "unusual movement" of Cameroonian troops 
stationed in Bakassi toward the Nigerian border area. "Up until 
yesterday, all we learned was that there was unusual movement of 
Cameroonian troops toward the Nigerian border," General Fred 
Chijuka, spokesman of the Defense Headquarters, told AFP. Gen. 
Chijuka, however, remarked that the movement of the Cameroonian 
troops does not necessarily mean that they have come "into 
contact" with Nigerian troops. "They are probably moving their 
troops closer to the border just in case hostilities break out," 
he said. Nigeria and Cameroon, which are claiming ownership of 
the Bakassi Peninsula, a 1,000-square-km zone rich in fish and 
oil, have stationed their troops at their borders. 

</TEXT>

