<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   PAC, MK Officers Complete Training Course </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2403202294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1951 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2403202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gweru March 24 SAPA -- Seventy-three Umhonto we 
Sizwe [Spear of the Nation -- African National Congress military 
wing; MK] and Azanian Peoples' Liberation Army [APLA] officers 
have graduated from a 12-week course for platoon commanders at 
the Zimbabwe Military Academy in Gweru. 
  The 22-week course was completed in record time so the 
officers could be in South Africa in time for the April 
elections, the ZIANA news agency reported on Thursday [24 
March]. The initial four-week phase equipped army officers with 
the knowledge and skills necessary for planning and supervising 
live firing. 
  The second phase, of five weeks, equipped them with basic 
knowledge of conventional warfare and the employment of platoon 
weapons and other support arms within a company setting. They 
were also provided with practical experience in the handling of 
a platoon in the field. 
  A third phase covered aspects of counter-insurgency and 
military law. 
  Reviewing officer Maj-Gen Philip Sibanda said Wednesday's 
graduation ceremony was a milestone in the history of the 
African sub-continent because the Zimbabwean Army had trained 
officers from the African National Congress and Pan Africanist 
Congress [PAC] simultaneously. 
  The officers and others who were being trained elsewhere in 
Zimbabwe would form the nucleus of South Africa's post-apartheid 
defence force. The officers are due to return to South Africa 
on Saturday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

