<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Botha Notes `Widespread Intimidation' in kwaZulu </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2503074294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2112 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2503074294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on news conference by Foreign Minister Pik Botha in </F>
Pretoria on 24 March by E. van Wyk] 
  [Text] Pretoria March 24 SAPA -- Foreign Affairs Minister 
Pik Botha on Thursday questioned the possibility of free and 
fair elections in kwaZulu in view of widespread intimidation. 
  At a news conference in Pretoria, Mr Botha warned of an 
"ominous possibility of bloodshed and conflict" in 
Natal/kwaZulu. He said he did not know to what extent kwaZulu 
chief minister and Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] leader Mangosuthu 
Buthelezi was prepared to allow the Independent Electoral 
Commission to do its work to ensure free and fair elections. 
  The fact was that the African National Congress [ANC] and 
the 
IFP were at war with each other, he said, suggesting that 
20-strong delegations of the ANC and the IFP under the 
chairmanship of an international figure or the chief justice 
meet to sort out their differences. "With so much intimidation 
in so many places there can hardly be a free and fair election." 
  Mr Botha warned of the danger that South Africa could be 
"forgotten" after the election and inauguration of the new 
president if the violence and intolerance did not come to an end. 
  He appealed to the ANC and the IFP to put South Africa 
first, 
rather than party political interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

